aws::graph::propositions: Military Variants of the Beechcraft Super King Air Model 200
The United States Army has flown versions of the Super King Air 200.
The United States Air Force has flown versions of the Super King Air 200.
The United States Navy has flown versions of the Super King Air 200.
The United States Marine Corps has flown versions of the Super King Air 200.
Some military Super King Air 200 versions were "off-the-shelf" civil versions.
The majority of military Super King Air 200 versions were purpose-built for the military.
Purpose-built military versions were treated by Beechcraft as a separate series.
Purpose-built military versions were treated by the Federal Aviation Administration as a separate series.
The separate series for military versions is designated the A200 series.
A significant minority of military versions are known purely by their military designations.
Some military versions have no Federal Aviation Administration model designations assigned to them.
Military versions without Federal Aviation Administration designations have basically equivalent civilian model counterparts.
The military designation for the Super King Air 200 varies from service to service.
Most military Super King Air 200 aircraft are called C-12 Huron.
Most military Super King Air 200 aircraft are called UC-12.
C-12 Huron and UC-12 aircraft are used for personnel transport.
The United States Army operates the RC-12 Guardrail series of aircraft.
The RC-12 Guardrail series is used for military intelligence missions.
The Canadian Forces Air Command took delivery of two second-hand early-production Model 200 Super King Airs in 1990.
The two Model 200 Super King Airs delivered to Canadian Forces Air Command were leased from Awood Air.

text:
#### Model 200 military variants

The United States Army, Air Force, Navy and Marine Corps have all flown versions of the Super King Air 200. As noted above some have been "off-the-shelf" civil versions, but the majority have been purpose-built for the military and were treated by Beechcraft and the FAA as a separate series, the A200 series. A significant minority of military versions are known purely by their military designations, with no FAA model designations being assigned to them, although they do have basically equivalent civilian model counterparts. The military designation varies from service to service, but most are called C-12 Huron or UC-12. These are used for personnel transport. The Army also operates the RC-12 Guardrail series of aircraft for military intelligence missions.
The Canadian Forces Air Command took delivery of two second-hand early-production Model 200 Super King Airs leased from Awood Air in 1990.
